EXERCISE:

  • Plot random effects against variables you feel might reveal a pattern
  • Experiment with the alternative RE model.

We will generate random effects from the following model

fitc <- lme( mathach ~ (ses + ses.m) * Sector, dd,
             random = ~ 1 + ses | school )
rand.eff<-ranef(fitc)

1.Plot of random effect of ses and the random intercept

There is a negative linear relationship between the intercept and the effect of ses on the math achievement. There is one influential outlier, without it the relationship might be even stronger.

2. Following are the plots of random effects against school size, proportion of sexes, sector and proportion of minority groups.

a) School size

It seems for largers schools the intercept tends to be higher, however there a few outliers that may affect the fit.

For larger schools effect of ses tends to become negative,but again there is an outlier that may affect the fit

b) Sex

The regression line in these graphs is meaningless since single gender schools are categorically different form mixed gender schools. But if we look at them separetly we can see that effect of ses is much greater in girl schools and is positively related to proportion of girls in mixed schools. Random intercept is however is lower for girl schools and is negatively related to the proportion of girls in mixed schools.

c) Sector

From above graph we can see that Catholic schools tend to have much greater variablility in intercept values and slopes.

d) Minority groups

It seems with higher the proportion of students from minority groups, the random intercept becomes less. This means that math achivement scores are generally lower. However there is a cluster of four outliers that have higher intercept and mostly minority students.

With increasing proportion negative effect of ses on math achivement increases, however the same four scools are dragging the regression line down. It would be interesting to look at those schools closer.

3. Lets change the random effects part of the model and see if anything changes.

In particular we will substitute ses with dvar(ses,id) which will give centeres within group variable.

fitc_dvar <- lme( mathach ~ (ses + ses.m) * Sector, dd,
             random = ~ 1 + dvar(ses,school) | school )
